{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":6998,"record_hash":"sha256:7dc2f900721e28869e9386d1b2b9aa92aeb0730d5ceb5c702419265100a0e140","timestamp":"2026-05-07T19:29:41.235Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: [REDACTED:entropy].md\n+# Agentlog Maintainability Playbook\n+\n+This note preserves the review approach for keeping `crates/but-agentlog`\n+small, maintainable, and intentionally authored. It is not a second spec. The\n+implementation contract still wins for behavior.\n+\n+## Source Material\n+\n+Useful references behind this playbook:\n+\n+- [Google Engineering Practices: What to look for in a code review](https://google.github.io/eng-practices/review/reviewer/looking-for.html)\n+- [Rust API Guidelines checklist](https://rust-lang.github.io/api-guidelines/checklist.html)\n+- [GitHub: Review AI-generated code](https://docs.github.com/en/copilot/tutorials/review-ai-generated-code)\n+- [Martin Fowler: Code Smell](https://martinfowler.com/bliki/CodeSmell.html)\n+- [Refactoring Guru: Speculative Generality](https://refactoring.guru/smells/speculative-generality)\n+- [Claude Code best practices](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/best-practices)\n+- [Simon Willison: First run the tests](https://simonwillison.net/guides/agentic-engineering-patterns/first-run-the-tests/)\n+\n+## What We Are Optimizing For\n+\n+The POC should feel like a careful GitButler crate, not generated scaffolding.\n+That means:\n+\n+- The code solves the problem we know exists now.\n+- Names are domain-specific and boring.\n+- Types carry meaning, but do not predict future product shape.\n+- Boundaries are obvious from reading the module names.\n+- Tests encode behavior and intent, not incidental implementation details.\n+- Comments explain rationale, privacy, or tricky failure modes. They do not\n+  narrate the next line.\n+\n+## Review Passes\n+\n+Run these as separate passes. Preserve behavior unless a specific bug is found.\n+\n+### 1. Deletion Pass\n+\n+Look for speculative generality:\n+\n+- one-use traits\n+- one-use structs\n+- generic helpers with only one real caller\n+- parameters added for imagined future agents\n+- fields that are always `None` or always the same value\n+- comments that repeat the code\n+\n+Delete or inline when the call site becomes clearer.\n+\n+### 2. Domain Naming Pass\n+\n+Rename vague concepts to the capture domain.\n+\n+Prefer:\n+\n+- `TranscriptRecord`\n+- `TranscriptEnvelope`\n+- `session_key`\n+- `source_record_hash`\n+- `write_capture`\n+\n+Avoid names that sound framework-like:\n+\n+- `Manager`\n+- `Processor`\n+- `Handler`\n+- `Adapter`\n+- `Service`\n+- `Provider`\n+\n+Only use a generic name when there is a real shared concept in Codex and Claude.\n+\n+### 3. Boundary Pass\n+\n+The intended shape is:\n+\n+```text\n+cli -> capture -> transcript parser -> gitmeta writer\n+                         |\n+                         v\n+                    redaction\n+```\n+\n+Check that:\n+\n+- CLI parsing and output stay in `cli.rs`.\n+- Repository resolution happens before business logic.\n+- Transcript parsing does not know GitMeta.\n+- GitMeta writing does not know provider-specific transcript vocabulary.\n+- Redaction only owns redaction.\n+- `but` CLI code remains a small feature-gated bridge.\n+\n+### 4. Rust API Pass\n+\n+Use Rust API Guidelines as a checklist, scaled down for a private POC crate:\n+\n+- Keep items private by default.\n+- Public crate surface should be only what `but` needs.\n+- Prefer `pub(crate)` over `pub` when cross-module access is needed.\n+- Keep typed errors at the library boundary.\n+- Use `anyhow` only in app/CLI glue.\n+- Prefer `&str` and `&Path` parameters when ownership is not needed.\n+- Avoid clones inside loops unless ownership is genuinely required.\n+- Derive `Debug` where it helps tests and diagnostics.\n+\n+### 5. Test Intent Pass\n+\n+Tests should answer: \"What behavior would break if a maintainer changed this?\"\n+\n+High-value tests for this crate:\n+\n+- malformed final JSONL line is skipped\n+- malformed middle JSONL line fails\n+- empty lines do not affect record indexes\n+- cwd mismatch fails\n+- dry-run performs no GitMeta writes\n+- repeated capture is idempotent\n+- transcript append dedupe survives missing hash set state\n+- Codex and Claude field extraction preserve the shared envelope shape\n+- redaction catches plausible secrets without schema-specific allowlists\n+\n+Avoid tests that only restate local implementation structure.\n+\n+### 6. AI-Specific Review Pass\n+\n+Ask reviewers or subagents narrow questions:\n+\n+- What looks over-generalized for a two-agent POC?\n+- What would a maintainer misunderstand six months from now?\n+- Which name hides a concrete domain concept?\n+- Which test would still pass if the behavior were subtly wrong?\n+- Which dependency, helper, or module exists only because generated code tends\n+  to over-structure things?\n+\n+Do not ask for a broad rewrite. The output should be small findings, not a new\n+architecture.\n+\n+## Cursor Note\n+\n+Do not force Cursor into the current JSONL parser path. Cursor's normal chat\n+history is local SQLite, and its documented portable flow is Markdown export.\n+That deserves a separate design pass later.\n+\n+## Validation Habit\n+\n+Before and after cleanup, run the narrow checks:\n+\n+```text\n+cargo fmt --check\n+cargo test -p but-agentlog\n+cargo check -p but --features agentlog\n+cargo clippy -p but-agentlog --all-targets --no-deps\n+cargo machete\n+```\n+\n+For behavior-neutral cleanup, the best result is boring: smaller code, clearer\n+names, and the same tests passing.\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T19:29:41.235Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}